I had a friend urging me to try it for awhile, read the first one, and didn't have a lot of ambition to do the second but finally did, and was so glad I did. The second one once it gets rolling gets it's hooks in. There's a lot of moments in the series that are just emotionally devastating.
It's a lot to handle though. 10 volumes, all of which are big, all of which have hundreds of characters, and it jumps around a lot. The scope is really, really wide.
The world building is denser than anything (the writer is an archaeologist by trade) and pretty merciless in assuming you're keeping up and reading between the lines.

Everything is big like the scope. Armies are huge, the setting spans continents, the pantheon of gods and magic is baroque and never explained, etc. It works though, maybe better than anything I've read.
I'm also a big fan of Joe Abercrombie's First Law series, Miles Cameron's Traitor Son cycle, and Scott Lynch's Gentleman Bastards series

text: Seems on-topic

His parents die and he's an orphan for awhile and gets to be tormented in a cool way. Then he gets to go to the best wizard school. Sure he has problems, because people are jealous of how badass of a wizard he is. Luckily he also gets to be the best musician ever too! What an amazing stroke of luck, being an amazing wizard AND an amazing musician, both super cool things you're the best at. The odds of that seem kinda crazy, but hey, suspension of disbelief, right? Wait, what's this? He's an amazing inventor too? Three things? Certainly there mustn't be anything else . . until he trains with ninjas and becomes the best swordsman! Wow! That certainly must be the end of the things our amazing hero can accomplish better than anyone, right? UNLESS HE FUCKS SOME FAERIES AND BECOMES THE BEST COCKSMAN IN THE LAND!
The farie fucking thing made me stop reading the book and go look up Rothfuss because that was the moment I was sure he was the Comic Book guy from the Simpsons, and sure enough he was.

Yeah, the bit with the fae was not my favorite. The whole training with ninjas thing was pretty cool, because the entire time he’s not a badass and spends the entirety of his time getting wrecked by literal children, cause he’s bad at it
Then again, they basically sign, so I might be biased

My favorite thing about Abercrombie's series is the characters themselves aren't really aware of the story they're in. I tried to explain it to my wife that it would be like if you had a book series about WWII, then a stand-alone about the Korean War where a private from the first series was now a General with new soldiers around him, then we got another book about a guy who us an old smuggler during the Vietnam War and you get some minor characters from the previous stories, and then realize the series is about America's rise as a military super power but nobody knows that, they just think they're living their own contained stories.
